ness, exploring how working-class atheists’ experiences of exclusion could make them sympathetic to other marginalised groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAtheismxSocial aspectsy19th century. 0aRacexPhilosophy. 0aRacexReligious aspects. 0aSecularizationxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aSecularizationxHistoryy19th centuryzUnited States. 0aSecularizationzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSecularizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / Atheism.2bisacsh  aAmerican history.  aAtheism.  aBritish history.  aChristianity.  aEmpire.  aFreethought.  aImperialism.  aRace.  aRacism.  aSecularism.1 aAlexander, Nathan G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614238240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526142382423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526142382/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles